@davisking thanks for the response last time. I re-installed boost using homebrew, and it seems to work now. 

I tried to compile dlib c++ example programs:
`cd dlib/examples;
mkdir build;
cd build;
cmake .. ;
cmake --build . --config Release` but got the error with the last step:

>[ 87%] Building CXX object CMakeFiles/dnn_imagenet_train_ex.dir/dnn_imagenet_train_ex.cpp.o
>In file included from /Users/HomeFolder/dlib/examples/dnn_imagenet_train_ex.cpp:12:
>In file included from /Users/HomeFolder/dlib/dlib/../dlib/dnn.h:14:
>In file included from /Users/HomeFolder/dlib/dlib/../dlib/dnn/layers.h:8:
>/Users/HomeFolder/dlib/dlib/../dlib/dnn/core.h:2444:45: fatal error: recursive template instantiation exceeded maximum depth of 256
            using next_type = typename std::remove_reference<decltype(makeT().subnet())>::type;

Is this a known issue?

I have a process running which continuously solves optimization problems with `solve_least_squares_lm`. I noticed that this process stalls seemingly at random with approximately with 12 hours in between (though this varies drastically).

This process runs on an embedded system so debugging is difficult but I managed to track down the culprit by inserting logging statements into dlib. Sometimes, the loop in [`dlib/optimization/optimization_trust_region.h`](https://github.com/davisking/dlib/blob/ca498ac2d214fd679f8c641f90d08fb63cac11f6/dlib/optimization/optimization_trust_region.h#L273) runs indefinitely. The loop in question is

    while(stale_x || stop_strategy.should_continue_search(x, f_value, g))

I use a custom `stop_strategy` which limits the number of iterations to a predefined value (5 in my case). I have a log statement as the first thing inside `should_continue_search`. When the stall occurs, I notice that `should_continue_search` isn't called anymore yet the operations inside the loop are still executed over and over. From that I infer that `stale_x` must be `true` and in turn short-circuiting the expression so that the `stop_strategy` isn't evaluated.

It is easy to track `stale_x` in the code. Inside the loop, it only occurs here

    if (rho > 0)
    {
        x = x + p;
        f_value = new_f_value;
        model.get_derivative_and_hessian(x,g,h);
        stale_x = false;
    }
    else
    {
        stale_x = true;
    }

So it must be that `0 >= rho` indefinitely when the loop never returns. `rho` is defined as

    const type rho = measured_improvement/std::abs(predicted_improvement);

Most likely, `0 >= measured_improvement` (though `predicted_improvement` could be really large as well). Apparently, the solver gets stuck (can't improve further `x` further) and this stalls the entire process.

To me it seems strange that we repeat the loop at all when `x` is stale. Why not simply

    if (0 >= rho)
    {
        break;
    }

and let go of `stale_x` completely? If no improvement could be made in this iteration, how could there be any improvement in the next (assuming that the subproblem solver is a pure function)?

